ce:section.ce:para:
Tortuosity was measured using DC-depolarization method in a symmetric cell geometry. Figure S5a is the schematic of the cell geometry used to determine Li+ diffusivity in different systems. A free-standing active-material film (CG or AGA-C electrodes, diameter = 8 mm) placed between the two Li-foils (diameter = 7 mm), and the separators (celgard 2325, diameter = 16 mm) were sandwiched between the active material and Li-foils. The symmetric cell geometry was used to measure the effective diffusivity (Deff
                        ). When active material film was replaced with a Polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) ring, whose external diameter is 16 mm and inner diameter is 8 mm, the device could value the intrinsic diffusivity (D0
                        ) of the electrolyte. The symmetric cells were assembled in an Ar-filled glove box. After that, the cells were allowed to stand for 2 h to make sure that the devices were wetted completely by liquid electrolyte (1 mol L−1 LiPF6 dissolved in ethylene carbonate and dimethyl carbonate, v/v=1/1). The assembled cells were tested using an electrochemical workstation (Bio-logic, VSP 300). The symmetric cell was polarized for 120 s at a constant current density (1.25 mAcm−2) to produce a concentration gradient. And then the current was interrupted to relax (depolarize) for a while until the cell potential (U) approached equilibrium (dU/dt < 0.1 mV h−1) during which record the open circuit voltage changes over time. As shown in Figure S5b-d, ln|U(t) − U(t = ∞)| versus time plot was constructed and linearly fitted in order determine the Li+ diffusivity (D0 and Deff) according to the eq. (3). And then tortuosity (τ) was calculated easily according to eq. (1).
